problem: Find an ordered pair $(u,v)$ that solves the system: \begin{align*} 5u &= -7 - 2v,\\ 3u &= 4v - 25 \end{align*}
solution: Multiplying the first equation by $2$ gives $10u = -14 - 4v$.  Adding this to the second equation gives $13u = -39$, so $ u= -3$.  Substituting this into $5u=-7-2v$ gives $-15=-7-2v$, so $v = 4$ and our solution is $(u,v) =\boxed{(-3,4)}$.
model_solution:
Step 1: Multiply the two equations by 2 and 3 respectively to clear the fractions, yielding \begin{align*} 10u &= -14 - 4v,\\ 9u &= 12v - 75 \end{align*}
Step 2: Subtract the first equation from the second equation to eliminate u, yielding $-u = 16v - 61$.
Substitute $u=\frac{61-16v}{-1}$ into the first equation of Step 1, yielding $10\left(\frac{61-16v}{-1}\right)=-14-4v$.
Simplify the equation by multiplying both sides by -1, yielding $-10(61-16v) = 14+4v$, which simplifies to $-610+160v = 14+4v$.
Add 610 to both sides and subtract 160v from both sides, yielding 446 = 164v.
Divide both sides by 164, yielding $v = \frac{446}{164}$.
Substitute $v = \frac{446}{164}$ into the equation $u=\frac{61-16v}{-1}$ and simplify to find u.
Substitute $v = \frac{446}{164}$ into $u = \frac{61 - 16v}{-1}$, yielding $u = \frac{61 - 16\left(\frac{446}{164}\right)}{-1}$, which simplifies to $u = \frac{61 - 278}{-1}$.
Simplify $u = \frac{61 - 278}{-1}$ to $u = \frac{-217}{-1}$.
Divide both sides by -1, yielding u = 217.
